{"author":"Iso Tester","data":{"fields":{"description":"# S5 ŌĆö Gerrit -> GitHub one-way replication (core plugin, non-force, deploy key)\n\n## Why\nMake Gerrit the sole writer of GitHub `main`. The core, Apache-2.0, WAR-bundled\n`replication` plugin (push) is the right tool ŌĆö the GerritForge BSL re-license (2025-09-30)\ntouched only `pull-replication` / multi-site, not this plugin. The non-force / `mirror=false`\n/ deploy-key choices form a deliberate one-way-door replication contract (Gerrit is the only\nwriter; GitHub history is append-only/fast-forward), so the rationale is captured as an ADR\n(see ## Files) rather than living only in this transient plan.\n\n## What\n- `replication.config` (`infra/gerrit/replication.config`):\n  - `push = refs/heads/main:refs/heads/main` + `push = refs/tags/*:refs/tags/*`\n    (NON-force ŌĆö no leading `+`).\n  - `mirror=false` (true does a destructive prune of remote refs absent/invisible locally).\n  - `replicatePermissions=false` (don't leak `refs/meta/config`); explicit refspecs so\n    `refs/changes/*` is never pushed.\n  - finite `replicationMaxRetries = 3`; `replicationDelay`/`timeout` bounded ŌĆö `timeout = 60`\n    (seconds). (Values are concrete so the implementer has no open \"choose an X\" decision;\n    they may be tuned at impl time but must remain finite/bounded ŌĆö unlimited retries are\n    forbidden, see AC.)\n- Identity: a single-repo, write-enabled, passphrase-less GitHub deploy key on the\n  `navapbc/rebar` repo (which currently has **0 deploy keys** ŌĆö S5 adds exactly one; the\n  GitHub-side bypass-listing of this key is S6's job, not S5's). The private key is sourced\n  from **SSM Parameter Store** at the path `/rebar/gerrit/github-deploy-key` (SecureString;\n  align with the project SSM naming convention if one is already established). The Gerrit\n  replication plugin's SSH client runs as the **Gerrit OS user** (`gerrit2`), so the key and\n  SSH config must be materialised in **that user's** home (`/home/gerrit2/.ssh/`), not root's.\n- Provisioning is **as-code and idempotent** (no hand-run steps): the GitHub deploy-key\n  registration + SSM parameter are managed by IaC (a Terraform `github_repository_deploy_key`\n  + `aws_ssm_parameter` pair, or an equivalent checked-in idempotent script under `infra/`),\n  and an init/entrypoint hook materialises the key from SSM onto disk and seeds `known_hosts`\n  **before** the replication plugin can fire its first push (ordering guarantee below).\n- **SSMŌåÆdisk materialisation + ordering (the most common failure mode):** an entrypoint /\n  init step, run as / writing to `gerrit2` and ordered **before** Gerrit's main process\n  starts (so it cannot race the first replication on a freshly-submitted change), must:\n  1. `aws ssm get-parameter --name /rebar/gerrit/github-deploy-key --with-decryption`,\n     writing the key to `/home/gerrit2/.ssh/id_ed25519` owned by `gerrit2` with mode `0600`;\n  2. seed GitHub's host key: `ssh-keyscan github.com >> /home/gerrit2/.ssh/known_hosts`\n     (so the first connection is non-interactive ŌĆö no host-key-verification prompt/failure);\n  3. write a `~/.ssh/config` `Host github.com` block whose `IdentityFile` points at that key.\n- **Lifecycle / rotation (one-way-door ŌĆö recorded in the ADR):** ownership of creation is\n  the IaC above. Rotation is the atomic sequence: generate new keypair ŌåÆ add the new GitHub\n  deploy key ŌåÆ update the SSM parameter ŌåÆ reload the Gerrit replication plugin ŌåÆ remove the\n  **old** GitHub deploy key (so there is no replication-outage gap). SSM stale versions are\n  pruned per the same procedure. The full provisioning + rotation + teardown is reproducible\n  from the checked-in IaC, not from operator memory.\n- **Observability:** a persistent alert (not just the one-time acceptance check) on\n  `replication_log` ERROR / max-retry-exhaustion entries ŌĆö a log-based metric + alarm\n  (CloudWatch/whatever the box already uses) so operators are notified when replication\n  stalls (e.g. revoked key, network partition, non-FF rejection) instead of GitHub silently\n  going stale. (Alternative weighed: Gerrit's `replication-status` SSH command polled by a\n  cron/healthcheck ŌĆö rejected as more moving parts than tailing the log the plugin already\n  writes; the log-based alarm reuses existing infra.)\n- **Rollback / kill-switch (S5 writes a shared external system ŌĆö GitHub `main` ŌĆö before\n  S6's branch protection exists, so reversibility matters):** replication can be disabled in\n  under 5 minutes without a full Gerrit redeploy by renaming the config and reloading the\n  plugin (`mv replication.config replication.config.disabled && ssh -p 29418 <gerrit> gerrit\n  plugin reload replication`), and, if the key is suspected compromised, revoking the GitHub\n  deploy key + rotating SSM. Recovery from a bad push (mis-config) is documented alongside.\n\n## Scope\nIn: replication plugin config + the deploy-key identity (SSMŌåÆdisk materialisation,\n`~/.ssh/config`, `known_hosts`) + as-code provisioning of the deploy key + push of `main` +\ntags + replication-failure alerting + a documented rollback/kill-switch + the ADR.\nOut: the GitHub-side lockdown that makes the mirror read-only (S6 ŌĆö GitHub branch protection\n/ bypass-listing the deploy key). **S5ŌåÆS6 ordering dependency (do not ignore):** because S5\nturns on non-force push **before** S6 forbids direct GitHub writes, there is a window where a\ndirect push to GitHub `main` would diverge it from Gerrit and cause every subsequent\nnon-force replication to be rejected with `non-fast-forward`. Mitigate by (a) deploying S6\nin the same change-set or promptly after S5, AND (b) the pre-activation prerequisite + the\nnon-FF alert below (so the window is bounded and monitored, not silent/indefinite).\n\n### Pre-activation prerequisite\nBefore enabling replication, verify GitHub `main` is fast-forwardable from Gerrit's HEAD:\n`git ls-remote https://github.com/navapbc/rebar refs/heads/main` HEAD must be an ancestor of\n(or equal to) Gerrit's `main` HEAD. If GitHub is already ahead (e.g. bootstrap commits), the\nfirst non-force push fails ŌĆö resolve the divergence first.\n\n## Files\n- `infra/gerrit/replication.config` ŌĆö the replication plugin config (push refspecs,\n  `mirror=false`, `replicatePermissions=false`, finite retries, timeout).\n- `infra/gerrit/entrypoint.sh` (or equivalent init hook) ŌĆö SSMŌåÆdisk key materialisation +\n  `ssh-keyscan` known_hosts seeding + `~/.ssh/config` write, run as `gerrit2` before Gerrit\n  starts.\n- `infra/` deploy-key provisioning as-code ŌĆö Terraform `github_repository_deploy_key` +\n  `aws_ssm_parameter` (SecureString at `/rebar/gerrit/github-deploy-key`) or a checked-in\n  idempotent script; includes teardown.\n- `infra/` replication-failure alert definition (log-based metric + alarm on\n  `replication_log` ERROR / max-retry).\n- `docs/adr/0005-gerrit-github-replication.md` ŌĆö ADR: plugin choice + BSL re-license\n  rationale, non-force / fast-forward-only policy, `mirror=false` reasoning, single-repo\n  deploy-key (vs OAuth/PAT) trade-off, key rotation/lifecycle as a one-way door, and the\n  pointer to S6 for GitHub-side enforcement.\n\n## Acceptance Criteria\n- [ ] A change submitted in Gerrit replicates `main` to `navapbc/rebar` on GitHub (non-force,\n      fast-forward) and tags replicate, verified by `replication_log` showing an exit-0 push\n      and `git ls-remote` reflecting the new SHA.\n- [ ] `refs/changes/*` and `refs/meta/config` are NOT pushed to GitHub, verified by inspecting\n      GitHub refs after replication (only `refs/heads/main` + `refs/tags/*` present), given the\n      explicit refspecs + `replicatePermissions=false`.\n- [ ] `mirror=false` is set (no destructive remote pruning), and `replicationMaxRetries` is a\n      finite value (e.g. 3, never unlimited) with a bounded `timeout`, verified by the config\n      file and by `replication_log` showing retries cap at that count.\n- [ ] **Non-force is enforced end-to-end:** given a GitHub `main` that cannot be\n      fast-forwarded from Gerrit (a diverged/extra commit on the GitHub side), the replication\n      push is **rejected** ŌĆö `replication_log` records a `non-fast-forward` failure (exit\n      non-zero) and GitHub history is **unchanged** (no force-overwrite). (Guards against a\n      `+` accidentally creeping into the refspec.)\n- [ ] The replication identity is a single-repo write deploy key whose private key is sourced\n      from SSM at `/rebar/gerrit/github-deploy-key` (no plaintext key committed to VCS); on\n      the Gerrit host, `/home/gerrit2/.ssh/id_ed25519` exists owned by `gerrit2` mode `0600`,\n      `~/.ssh/config` routes the `github.com` connection to it, and `known_hosts` is\n      pre-seeded with GitHub's host key.\n- [ ] A pre-activation SSH smoke-test passes as an evidence gate **before** the config goes\n      live: `sudo -u gerrit2 ssh -T git@github.com` from the Gerrit host returns GitHub's\n      \"successfully authenticatedŌĆ” does not provide shell access\" banner (exit non-interactive,\n      no host-key prompt) ŌĆö i.e. identity + known_hosts are proven before any real push.\n- [ ] Deploy-key + SSM provisioning is reproducible **as-code**: re-running the IaC/script on\n      a clean host re-creates the GitHub deploy key, the SSM parameter, the on-disk key, and\n      `known_hosts` with no manual steps; a teardown path is documented.\n- [ ] A persistent replication-failure alert is in place: an ERROR / max-retry entry in\n      `replication_log` (e.g. revoked key, `non-fast-forward`) triggers an operator\n      notification (the alarm fires in a test/dry-run), so a silent stall during the S5ŌåÆS6\n      window is detected.\n- [ ] The pre-activation FF prerequisite is documented and checked: GitHub `main` is an\n      ancestor of (or equal to) Gerrit's `main` HEAD at activation time.\n- [ ] A rollback/kill-switch is documented and works: replication can be disabled in under 5\n      minutes via `mv replication.config replication.config.disabled` + `gerrit plugin reload\n      replication` (verified by `replication_log` showing no new attempts), with deploy-key\n      revocation as the compromise path.\n- [ ] `docs/adr/0005-gerrit-github-replication.md` exists and captures the replication-contract\n      decisions (non-force, `mirror=false`, single-repo deploy key, rotation lifecycle,\n      S5ŌåÆS6 ordering) so the rationale survives the plan ticket."}},"env_id":"ade0f2ef-51cc-45a2-bb97-c09846cd3df5","event_type":"EDIT","timestamp":1782689172533284001,"uuid":"349364b1-6159-48fd-9b80-a31e41f255bd"}